(807, 'PBHA&#39;s Franklin I-O Summer Program', 'The Franklin I-O Summer Program serves 80 children and their families from the Franklin Field and Franklin Hill housing developments in Dorchester.  The program aims to provide year-round academic support in conjunction with the Franklin After-School Education (FASE) and Franklin Teen programs; help overcome gang violence and other challenging conditions of the urban ghetto by bringing the children together in a safe, enriching, and fun environment; and foster relationships between the children and Counselors of diverse backgrounds where learning is reciprocal. The inter-generational camp brings together fun-loving children aged 6-13, ambitious local teenagers as Junior Counselors, passionate college-aged Senior Counselors, and the local elderly community.  Senior and Junior Counselors engage the campers in a curriculum that works to build self-esteem and aid them in making informed decisions by supporting them in exploring their identity, values, and physical world.  The curriculum incorporates math, science, reading, and writing in a dynamic way that stimulates the campers&#39; interest in learning and is complemented by daily exciting and educational field trips throughout the Boston area and beyond, as well as collaborations with other community groups.  For the ten-week program, Senior Counselors receive training, a stipend, housing, and an unforgettable experience.  Successful applicants will possess passion...for sharing... learning...service...and fun.  No experience necessary.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(808, 'PBHA&#39;s Keylatch Summer', 'The Keylatch Summer Program provides under-served children from Boston&#39;s South End with a high quality, enriching summer camp experience. Community leaders, families and Keylatch staff engage campers in activities that allow them to explore new opportunities, deepen cultural and community pride, and foster a love of learning.  In creating and sharing in this experience, college and high school - age staff members gain tangible leadership skills, a deeper understanding of themselves, and a compelling awareness of social service.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(809, 'PBHA&#39;s Mission Hill Summer Program', 'The Mission Hill Summer Program (MHSP) is a seven-week, affordable, academic camp which serves families from Roxbury&#39;s Mission Main and Alice Taylor Housing Developments, both predominantly African American and Latino communities. Founded at the request of community members, the camp seeks to provide a safe space for the 80 campers, ages 6 to 13, for the price of $95 for the entire summer. Each morning is strictly academic, as campers learn literacy and math in order to prevent summer learning loss and prepare them for the next year in the classroom. In the afternoons, the campers go on field trips and perform their own service projects across the greater Boston area in order to provide them with deeper experiences within their greater community than they generally get in school. MHSP provides crucial services for families who struggle to find affordable, innovative childcare. Many have siblings in the program and return year after year, and MHSP has become a fixture in the community. MHSP also hires 12 teens from the community to work as Junior Counselors. Senior Counselors will live in Roxbury and will work closely with the families of their campers.  MHSP is looking for committed counselors with an interest in poverty, social justice, social work, and education.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(810, 'PBHA&#39;s Native American Youth Enrichment Program (NAYEP)', 'NAYEP is a 7-week summer program for Native American children ages 6-13. Unlike most summer programs, we are not geographically centered.  NAYEP serves children of all tribal ancestries from all across the Boston area.  Senior counselors each lead a group of 8-10 children between 9 am and 4 pm on weekdays.  Our mornings are focused on curriculum, our afternoons are usually reserved for field trips and constructive recreation (such as swimming lessons). Curriculum is developed by each senior counselor and therefore changes each summer, but all major academic areas are covered.  We also spend a great deal of focus on Native culture, history, myth and identity, as well as health and environmental issues, multiculturalism, and developing creativity.  Each senior counselor has a classroom in the basement of NAICOB, the North American Indian Center of Boston.  We have a particular challenge in that our campers come from all kinds of social and economic backgrounds.  In-depth knowledge/experience in Native Issues is not necessarily a prerequisite for the job of senior counselor.  Anyone with a real interest in learning and teaching is welcomed and encouraged to apply.', '', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~NAYEP', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(811, 'PBHA&#39;s Roxbury Youth Initiative (RYI)', 'Roxbury Youth Initiative is designed to give academic enrichment and personal support to campers aged 6 through 13 from the Roxbury community. All summer long, the camp provides daily morning classroom academics, which are geared toward teaching fundamental concepts in math, science, and literacy as well as teaching concepts and ideas in the areas of government and history. The afternoons are spent participating in field trips and activities that supplement the learning received in the classroom, as well as provide a source of recreation for the children. The goal is to not only promote academic achievement, but also to cultivate excitement about learning, to expose Roxbury children to a world not yet discovered by them, to foster an understanding of how integral they are to the world, and to give the children concrete tolls that they may use later in life to participate and better this world in its greater sense.  Roxbury Youth initiative initially began as two separate camps serving the communities of Academy Homes and Dudley, which are both in Roxbury. Last year these two were combined allowing the program to serve Roxbury as one entity. Roxbury is a predominantly African-American and Latino community located in Boston.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(812, 'PBHA&#39;&#39;s Refugee Youth Summer Enrichment', 'Created in 1986 in response to the needs of the growing immigrant refugee population in the Greater Boston area, RYSE today serves more than 100 students from various Greater Boston communities. The mission of RYSE is to create a small yet intimate environment to provide affordable ESL instruction to high school refugee and immigrant students. As a part of this instruction, we offer an introduction to American culture and a chance to shape the experience of our students. As a 7-week intensive summer program that runs five nights a week (Monday through Friday), three hours each night (4:30-7:30 pm), RYSE provides ESL instruction in the context of a cultural exchange. We hope to provide a concrete and cultural understanding of the language by utilizing both formal and hands-on teaching methods, and incorporating community service projects and educational field trips in the curriculum. By working closely with students, parents, community members and organizations, RYSE strives to facilitate the cultural integration of refugee youths into American society, help them realize their tremendous potential and provide them with the necessary tools and skills to succeed in their academic and personal growth.  During term-time, many of the RYSE students are enrolled in the Refugee Youth Term-Time Enrichment (RYTE) program, which is a sister program of RYSE that helps to maintain year-round cohesive support to the students.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(813, 'PBHA&#39;s South Boston Outreach Summer (SBOS)', 'South Boston Outreach Summer Program provides a summer day camp for at-risk children whose mothers are working to further their education through the Julie&#39;s Family Learning Program in South Boston.  Our forty-four campers, ages 6-13, come primarily from the Old Colony and West Broadway public housing developments in South Boston.	South Boston Outreach encompasses education, diversity, and social responsibility through hands-on activities and field trips.  Campers explore their own community as well as the larger city around them in order to understand their own ethnic heritage and to appreciate the diversity of Boston.  Also, our two overnight camping trips give campers a chance to work together as a team, discover nature, and learn basic environmental awareness.  During the summer, counselors live in an apartment in the Old Colony Housing Project, which allows us to become full-time members of the community and develop social bonds with campers and their families.  The senior counselor salary is $3400.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Feb 23, 2011'),
(818, 'Respectably French!', 'Respectably French! is Harvard&#39;s only (and therefore, the best) video sketch comedy group. RF! members write, direct, produce, edit and distribute original material for web viewing and for occasional comedy show screenings.   The organization provides many opportunities for students to further refine (or learn for the first time) skills related to screenwriting, cinematography, video editing, and acting.  Occasionally, RF! helps organize campus wide events, and has even welcomed various celebrities in past years.', 'RespectablyFrench@gmail.com', 'http://www.respectablyfrench.com', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(819, 'Global Initiative for Women&#39;s Empowerment', 'The mission of GIVE is to create a diverse, international network for organizations promoting women&#39;&#39;s empowerment. Through this network, we aim to connect the Harvard student community to global initiatives for women including, but not limited to, women&#39;&#39;&#39;&#39;s health, political rights, economic empowerment, and ending domestic violence.\r\n\r\nGIVE aims to achieve this goal in three ways. First, GIVE will form and maintain, both online and in print, a searchable database of internationally-located non-governmental organizations (NGOs) actively working for the advancement of women and able to accept student interns. Second, GIVE will form and maintain an online and in-print journal of field reports from Harvard students who have worked for community empowerment abroad. Third, GIVE will work closely with selected NGOs dedicated to women&#39;&#39;s empowerment, to facilitate funding search, grant writing, volunteer recruitment, website development, creation of internet-based document libraries, and effective use of available technology to increase NGO visibility.  This student-NGO partnership will be a sustainable program to connect Harvard students to international work for women&#39;&#39;s empowerment.', 'help@harvardgive.org', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates', 'March', 'Sep 04, 2012'),
(825, 'Half Asian People&#39;s Association', 'The purpose of Hapa is to provide a forum at Harvard for students to come together to discuss issues of mixed-ethnicity, especially mixed-Asian ethnicities. The club hopes foster community through social meetings, as well as sponsor educational and awareness-building events. HAPA shall provide a space for its members to voice their opinions and comfortably explore their culture, identity, and\r\nindividuality.', 'harvardhapa@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/harvardhapa/index.html', '51-75', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(826, 'Board Riders Association', 'The Board Riders Association of Harvard College allows students with an interest in surfing, windsurfing, and kiteboarding to congregate and experience contemporary political, social, and cultural issues regarding the sport of surfing. The group will seek to promote greater awareness and understanding of these issues in the Harvard community by appropriate means such as publications, meetings, seminars, and other educational activities.  A further goal would be to assist in the integration of freshman surfers to the East Coast.', 'icarter@college.harvard.edu', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 24, 2012'),
(828, 'Phillips Brooks House Association (PBHA)', 'PBHA is a student-run public service organization at Harvard University. \r\n\r\nConsisting of 84 program committees, over 1,600 student volunteers, and serving close to 10,000 constituents in the Cambridge and Boston area, PBHA is an organization dedicated to Social Service and Social Action.  \r\n\r\nAs a student-run organization, we draw upon the creative initiative of students and community members to foster collaboration that empowers individuals and communities. Through social service and social action, PBHA endeavors to meet community needs and promote social awareness and community involvement at Harvard and beyond.', 'pbha@pbha.org', 'www.pbha.org', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'November', 'Oct 31, 2012'),
(829, 'Corcairdhearg Harvard College Irish Dancers', 'Irish Dancing is an expression of athleticism, talent, and culture.  It is both an artful and competitive activity in which thousands of students participate worldwide.  Modern Irish Dancing derives from traditional step dancing, which became popular in Ireland during the 18th Century.  Unique characteristics distinguished Irish step dancing from other forms of dance, and dancers became known for their rigid upper bodies, precise movements, and percussive beats.  Today, Irish Dancing has become a popular modern form of dance throughout all of Europe, Australia, and the Americas.  Dancers learn a variety of steps choreographed to traditional Irish music; the dances may be performed in light shoes or heavy shoes, as solo dances or as team dances.  \r\nThe Harvard College Irish Dancers, named &#xFFFD;Corcairdhearg&#xFFFD; after the Irish word for &#xFFFD;Crimson,&#xFFFD; are a group of students dedicated to choreographing, practicing, and performing Irish Dancing at Harvard.  The group serves three functions to incorporate all levels of dancing.  Firstly, the dancers showcase their work by participating in various cultural shows on campus and by holding performances of their own.  Weekly practices allow the students to create and perfect new steps and to share different styles of the dance with one another.  Secondly, the group holds classes for inexperienced dancers to learn the basics of Irish Dancing.  Finally, the group forms a network for currently competitive dancers to give these students an opportunity to continue competing throughout their time at Harvard.  \r\nCorcairdhearg:  Harvard College Irish Dancers is a group committed to bringing this unique form of dance to the Harvard community.', 'harvardirishdance@gmail.com', 'hcs.harvard.edu/~irishdance', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'September', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(831, 'Tempus-The Harvard College History Review', 'Tempus: The Harvard College History Review is the History Department&#39;s undergraduate journal. Tempus was founded by a pair of undergraduates in 1998 as a forum for for publishing original historical scholarship through which all students have the opportunity to learn from their peers. Tempus also sponsors history events and aims to promote an undergraduate community within the Department. In the spring of 2009, Tempus became an online publication.', 'tempushchr@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/tempus/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(833, 'Kidney Disease Screening and Awareness Program', 'The mission of the Kidney Disease Screening and Awareness Program (KDSAP) is to increase public awareness and early detection of chronic kidney disease. Our focus centers on underserved, minority communities in Greater Boston, which are at greater risk for end-stage renal disease due to genetics, as well as linguistic and socioeconomic barriers to health. Through collaborating with Boston-area nephrologists, we hope to alleviate this health disparity and improve access to culturally competent care by organizing free kidney health screenings, giving health education talks to the community, and referring at-risk individuals to health care providers. Lastly, KDSAP organizes a variety of on-campus speaker events, shadowing opportunities, and a mentorship program for students interested in public health, science, and medicine.', 'kdsapdirect@gmail.com', 'http://harvardkdsap.wix.com/main', '76-100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(834, 'Japan Initiative', 'Harvard College Japan Initiative is a student-run organization dedicated to fostering greater interaction and understanding between students from the U.S. and Japan. Its mission is twofold: to encourage Japanese students to rethink the Japanese education system and explore ways to improve it, and to tackle the issue of the under-representation of Japanese students in universities outside of Japan, especially at Harvard University. Specifically, the Harvard College Japan Initiative aims to inform Japanese high school and college students about opportunities to study in the U.S., and to guide interested students through the admissions and financial aid processes. It also aims to promote the exchange of ideas and perspectives between Harvard students and Japanese students through discussions about political and social issues surrounding U.S. -Japan relations.\r\nIn order to undertake these missions, the Harvard College Japan Initiative will hold an annual summer conference in Tokyo, aimed at Japanese high school students, in partnership with Japanese universities and alumni from Harvard and other U.S. colleges.', 'board@hcji.org', 'http://www.hcji.org/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'September', 'Nov 28, 2012'),
(836, 'Stories for Orphans', 'Harvard College Stories for Orphans integrates students&#39; interests in creative writing, drawing, and foreign languages, coordinating their creative efforts for the benefit of orphaned children abroad. It is our hope that by presenting each child with a book written, illustrated, and bound especially for him, we will inspire a love of reading and of self.', 'stories@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://hcs.harvard.edu/stories', '51-75', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'January', 'Sep 11, 2012'),
(838, 'Bioethics Society', 'The goal of the Harvard Undergraduate Bioethics Society (HUBS) is to examine ethical issues brought forth by advances in science and medicine through discussion, investigation, research, and analysis of biology, biotechnology, genetics, medicine, theology, philosophy, politics, law, and other relevant topics that affect ethical decision-making on our campus and in our world.', 'harvardbioethics@gmail.com', 'www.hcs.harvard.edu/bioethics', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Nov 07, 2012'),
(841, 'Team HBV', 'Team HBV at Harvard College recognizes the pressing need to address ethnic health disparities and, in particular, the disproportionate incidence of Hepatitis B Virus (HBV) in the Asian and Pacific Islander population, both domestically and globally. The organization strives to organize effective campus and community-wide events to raise awareness about the disease, offer increased access to screenings and vaccinations, and strengthen political advocacy for hepatitis B.  In addition to fostering educational foundation and opening multidisciplinary dialogues on campus, we also implement outreach initiatives and mobilize collective support on the community level. Team HBV at Harvard College will draw from a variety of perspectives in public health, preventive medicine, and health policy to effect real change with a specific focus.', 'harvard@teamhbv.org', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/teamhbv/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'October', 'Dec 04, 2012'),
(844, 'Composers Association', 'The mission of the Harvard Composers Association is to promote the presence of 20th and 21st century music on campus through concerts of contemporary repertoire, original student compositions and collaborative projects with other mediums, art forms and organizations. We work with musicians from the Harvard community and beyond, usually members of our unofficial organization, the Harvard New Music Ensemble - a group of top student musicians who have a dedicated interest in new music. This allows student composers to have their works rehearsed and performed by musicians of the highest caliber, which is the most important thing for an aspiring composer.\r\n\r\nWe also began a small new music festival - &quot;Atelier&quot; - starting in the spring of 2011, that brought together composers and performers for a series of masterclasses and rehearsals, culminating in a concert in Paine Hall.\r\n\r\nHCA believes in the relevance of contemporary music created in the Classical tradition in modern society and the importance of new music if Classical Music is to be recognized as a living art form. Such status can only result from performances, as well as the advocating and promotion of new music.', 'hrcme@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(845, 'Seeding Labs', 'Talent is everywhere, but resources are not. There is a wealth of funds and resources available to scientists in the United States that often goes to waste, while researchers in developing countries lack the ability to buy even basic laboratory equipment. Seeding Labs hopes to address this disparity by collecting used and surplus laboratory equipment from universities, hospitals, and biotechnology companies to supply scientists in the developing world with the tools they need to conduct their research. Ultimately, we would like to integrate the researchers in these labs into a global collaborative community of scientists, sharing expertise across national boundaries, advancing global research and training the next generation of scientists.', 'hcseedinglabs@gmail.com', 'www.seedinglabs.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(861, 'Global Hunger Initiative', 'The Harvard College Global Hunger Initiative works to address the underlying causes of the global food crisis by brainstorming and developing new models that can alleviate the recent food shortage, advance education, improve technologies, increase economic opportunity, and tackle the root challenges in poverty alleviation. We advocate for policies that increase emergency aid to those affected by the hunger crisis, as well as long-term developmental programs in affected countries. We aim to have an agenda of both action and advocacy, bridging students from the undergraduate, graduate, and professional schools, as well as community members in Cambridge and Allston to alleviate global hunger.  We are committed to helping families in poor communities improve their lives and achieve lasting victories over poverty.  We pursue our mission with both compassion and commitment.  With action as our priority, the Harvard College Global Hunger Initiative will focus on brainstorming and crafting actionable responses to challenges in agriculture, by focusing mainly on: (i) technology and innovation, (ii) public and economic policy, (iii) environment and its disproportionate effects on agricultural communities, (iv) education and the empowerment of women, and (v) access to clean and safe drinking water, which is often coupled with the scarcity of food. The Harvard College Global Hunger Initiative will do more than raise consciousness &ndash; it will provide substantive ways to engage students in brainstorming, developing, and testing models. Current solutions to alleviating the global food crisis has shown to be frail in recent years.  We need creativity, novel thinking, and the bridging of disciplines to create sustainable models to tackle developmental challenges.', 'globalhungerinitiative@gmail.com', 'www.globalhungerinitiative.com', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'February', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(870, 'On Harvard Time', 'On Harvard Time (OHT) is Harvard&#39;s premier source of quality comedy, with its bi-weekly, around 8-minute, entirely online comedy news show and related activities, including collaborative efforts with other on-campus comedy groups such as our Comedy Extravaganzas, LMAO, and more. OHT&#39;s aim is to report and lampoon on what&#39;s happening at Harvard University, provide a look into what life is like at Harvard, and give the Harvard perspective on national and international new as well. It aims to enrich the community with humor about, self-deprecation of, and celebration for Harvard. OHT also provides undergraduates an incredible opportunity to learn and hone their skills in business, marketing, writing, camerawork, technical work, directing, producing, and reporting in an inclusive and fun broadcast television environment.', 'onharvardtime@gmail.com', 'http://www.onharvardtime.com', '51-75', 'Undergraduates', 'February', 'Sep 17, 2012'),
(872, 'Alpha Omega', 'Harvard College Alpha Omega (HCA&Omega;) seeks to discuss issues of faith, reason, and spirituality within the Christian tradition and to explore how these concern the Harvard community; to enrich understanding of Christianity and of the Restoration Movement among faculty and students; to foster an exchange of ideas concerning the identity and purpose of the Restoration Movement, both within Christianity and within the global religious community; and to provide a center for fellowship among students and faculty interested in the Restoration Movement, especially for members of the Disciples of Christ, the Independent Christian Churches, the Churches of Christ, the International Churches of Christ, and the non-institutional Churches of Christ.', 'alphaomega@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/alphaomega', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'September', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(873, 'Social Enterprise Association', 'HCSEA is a student-run organization that strives to promote and engage in social enterprise, the application of the belief that business methods and entrepreneurship can achieve scalable and sustainable improvement in the world (including for-profit, non-profit, and non-governmental organizations).  Our mission is to educate, motivate and connect students in order to establish the next generation of leaders in social enterprise and non-profit social sector. In the recent years, HCSEA has been focusing on organizing student trip to the developing world to collaborate with local social organizations.', 'hc.socialenterprise@gmail.com', 'www.harvardsea.org', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Sep 21, 2012'),
(878, 'Reserve Officer Training Corps Association', 'The purpose of the HROTCA is to create a united group on campus for students interested in military service or military careers, with a focus on opportunities in college.  The group will seek to provide support for those already in the services, information to those interested in the services, and an environment for better understanding and appreciation of military service.', 'harvardrotc@gmail.com', 'http://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=2200053719&amp;ref=ts', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'September', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(879, 'Digital Literacy Project', 'The Digital Literacy Project is a collaborative effort among Harvard students who are interested in the intersection between education and technology. The group is part of an international grassroots movement that promotes 1-1 computing throughout the developing world. Although the group is unaffiliated with One Laptop per Child, the founders believe that the XO laptop is an exciting way to narrow the digital divide. The Digital Literacy Project has pilot programs at the Cambridge Friends School and the Mission Hill School in the Boston area, and has created a self-sustaining deployment in Managua, Nicaragua. The group plans to create more local and international deployments in the coming years.\r\n	The Digital Literacy Project has four primary objectives, which include (1) organizing educational pilot programs in elementary and middle schools in the Boston area and internationally, (2) generating a formal outreach platform that can be tailored to fit the needs of schools, (3) engaging the Boston community in a discussion of cost-effective computing for children by hosting events at museums and after-school programs, and (4) providing a forum for Harvard students to discuss how interactive technologies may be introduced to young people all over the world.', 'info@DigiLiteracy.org', 'http://www.digiliteracy.org/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(886, 'Initiating Mutual Understanding through Student Exchange', 'IMUSE is a non&#x2010;profit organization founded and run by students at Harvard, the Tsinghua University Association for Students&rsquo; International Communication, and the Peking University Students&rsquo; International Communication Association that aims to foster mutual curiosity, respect, and understanding among people in China and the outside world by providing top college and graduate students and future leaders from around the globe an intimate forum for both formal and informal communication and deep personal reflection about the issues challenging the relationship and development of both regions today.', 'admin@imusefoundation.org', 'http://www.projectimuse.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'July', 'Sep 11, 2012'),
(887, 'Lowell House Society of Russian Bell Ringers at Harvard College', 'The Lowell House Society of Russian Bell Ringers at Harvard College promotes the study and practice of the ringing of Russian bells in the Harvard community, performing regularly on the Lowell House bells and encouraging exchange visits and historical research.', 'bells-list@lists.hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.lowell.harvard.edu/Bells/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'May', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(889, 'Synthesis', 'Synthesis is an organization dedicated to promoting ties within the history of science academic community at Harvard and publishing a yearly interdisciplinary history of science journal.', 'synthesisjournal@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~hsdept/news.html', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Nov 14, 2012'),
(890, 'Health Advocacy Program', 'The mission of HAP is to empower youth to be proactive about their own health through a hands-on nutrition-based curriculum and to become leaders by promoting healthy lifestyles among their families and peers. HAP achieves its mission by making students aware of the barriers that prevent them from gaining good health and by guiding them through a project to overcome those barriers. We wish to develop leaders who are not afraid to take on health challenges in their community.', 'hap.harvard@gmail.com', 'http://healthadvocacyprogram.wordpress.com', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Community Members', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(891, 'Dynamo', 'Dynamo is a community of science enthusiasts and scholars dedicated to fostering interdisciplinary scientific discourse and innovation in the Harvard undergraduate community.', 'dynamo@lists.hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~dynamoweb/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(893, 'Ivory Tower', 'Ivory Tower aims to provide students with a ground-level introduction to the making of serial television on campus. We welcome and encourage writers, directors, producers, singers, songwriters, and actors alike to come and participate and work together to create a year-long project representative of the strengths each brings to the table. It also provides students with an opportunity to work in business or in public relations with the community. Above all, as the United States&rsquo; longest running college program, the organization is dedicated to the production of quality entertainment for the undergraduates of Harvard College and of those beyond our walls.', 'dartekmovie@gmail.com', 'http://hutvnetwork.com/shows/ivorytower', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Community Members', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(897, 'Faith and Action', 'Harvard College Faith and Action is a gospel-centered community that welcomes students from all backgrounds. Our ministry emphasizes leadership development, rigorous study of scripture, social justice initiatives and active involvement in campus life. We encourage every student to pursue their calling as servant, disciple and leader, growing in the likeness and knowledge of Jesus Christ.', 'hcfanda@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~hcfa/', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(901, 'Shani A Cappella', 'Shani (Hebrew for &quot;crimson&quot;) is Harvard&#39;s Jewish a cappella group, founded in Fall 2007 by Jhosh Friedman &#39;08 and Ilan Caplan &#39;10. With a repertoire ranging from Debbie Friedman to 16th-century liturgical arrangements, Shani performs primarily for local nursing homes and charity fund-raising events. The group&#39;s commitment to social action work through Jewish music blends with a healthy dose of humor and a warm inclusivity among performers and audience alike.', 'shanimeanscrimson@gmail.com', 'http://hillel.harvard.edu/undergraduates/affiliated-groups/shani', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(906, 'Association for the Promotion of Interplanetary Expansion', 'The purpose of HAPIE is to bring together people interested in human settlement beyond earth and to engage such people in social activities, primarily board games.  The long term goal is to advocate for and eventually achieve human settlements on other planets.', 'HAPIEmail@gmail.com', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'February', 'Sep 21, 2012'),
(917, 'Peruvian Association', 'The Harvard College Peruvian Association has a dual purpose: to provide a space for students who share an interest in Peruvian society and to serve as a liaison between the Harvard and Peruvian communities.', 'harvard.peru@gmail.com', 'www.hcs.harvard.edu/~hcpa', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 21, 2012'),
(918, 'Madrigal Singers', 'We, The Harvard College Madrigal Singers, are a mixed ensemble of twelve to sixteen vocalists dedicated to sharing our passion for classical choral works through performance. Our purpose is to provide musicians at Harvard College with a unique opportunity to sing and perform classical, mostly pre-1900 a cappella music, and to do so in a small ensemble.  As an organization led and conducted entirely by students, we seek to promote musical leadership and a passion for the arts both on campus and in the greater community. We are also committed to helping each member develop his musicianship and will hold extra sight singing, ear training, etc. sessions as the needs and desires of choir members require.', 'harvardmadrigalsingers@gmail.com', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'May', 'Sep 24, 2012'),
(923, 'Advocating Success for Kids', 'In order to help eliminate the link between low income and diminished access to education, the ASK program advocates on behalf of children with special needs so they can benefit from resources for academic success.', 'advocatingsuccessforkids@gmail.com', 'https://sites.google.com/site/advocatingsuccess/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 04, 2012'),
(927, 'UNICEF', 'The overall goal of Harvard College UNICEF is to spread awareness of the situation of the world&rsquo;s children, and to encourage members to take action to help save lives. Harvard College UNICEF&rsquo;s efforts will focus on increasing local awareness about UNICEF&rsquo;s mission both on campus and in the community.\r\n	Harvard UNICEF aims to 1) educate members on the state of the health and education of the world&rsquo;s children 2) raise funds to be used towards UNICEF&rsquo;s work with these children, and 3) provide opportunities for members to directly advocate to protect the lives of children in need. \r\n	Harvard College UNICEF has an influence and opportunity that reaches beyond life at college. Passionate members who wish to continue working with UNICEF after graduation may do so on an individual basis by volunteering at www.unicefusa.org/volunteer, or through participating in collective initiatives, trips, and boards.', 'hunicef@gmail.com', 'N/A', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(928, 'Black Christian Fellowship', 'The Harvard College Black Christian Fellowship (HCBCF) is a student group committed to seeing Jesus&rsquo; hope and restoration come to the Black Community at Harvard.  HCBCF seeks to nurture deep relationships with God and each other through Bible Study, worship, fellowship and service in the Harvard community and beyond.', 'hrbcf-announce@lists.hcs.harvard.edu', 'https://lists.hcs.harvard.edu/mailman/listinfo/hrbcf-announce', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Oct 12, 2012'),
(933, 'Cyber Defense Club', 'Expand the knowledge of students at Harvard University through hands-on application and competition with other universities. Communicate Harvard University as a center for Computer Science excellence. Establish a network of Cyber Security aware alumni in the Harvard University family. Create a forum for undergraduate students interested in cyber security. Provide a medium for professors, graduate students, and industry Cyber Security Subject Matter Experts to share their knowledge with Harvard University Cyber Defense club undergraduates. Create Harvard University Cyber Security Subject Matter Experts to facilitate the transition to job opportunities. Use the Regional and National Collegiate Cyber Security Competition competition as a metric of Harvard University CS expertise maturation.', 'harvardcyberdefense@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/cyberdefense', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(935, 'Cube Club', 'The purpose of the Harvard College Cube Club (HCCC) is to bring together the community of puzzle solvers, in particular of the Rubik&rsquo;s cube, at Harvard.  Furthermore, this organization reaches out to those who are simply interested in learning to solve a Rubik&rsquo;s cube or get involved in the art of Cubing.', 'ccubed@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'December', 'Nov 05, 2012'),
(939, 'Photography Club', 'The overall goal of the Harvard Photography Club will be to provide student photographers with the resources and artistic community they require to develop and grow their photographic skills. This community will give students inspiration and instruction through interaction with their fellow photographers, and help advance the visual arts on the Harvard campus.', 'harvardphotoclub@gmail.com', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Nov 28, 2012'),
(940, 'Future Society', 'The Harvard College Future Society promotes awareness and further understanding of the link between accelerating technological growth and future society.\r\n \r\nIn the presence of rapidly expanding human intelligence and vastly augmented capabilities, we will be soon be compelled to radically reevaluate our most fundamental ideas of what it means to be human, and we will need to discover a way for humans to live in a rapidly changing world. Previously unimaginable technologies may become concrete reality in the coming decades, and decisions will have to be made.  \r\n\r\nThe Harvard College Future Society provides a forum to discuss various visions of humanity&#39;s future in light of technological growth. Some topics of interest include Transhumanism, Artificial Intelligence, 3D Printing, and others.', 'hfs@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://harvardcollegefuturesociety.wordpress.com/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Sep 16, 2012'),
(941, 'Hellenic Society', 'The overall goal of the Harvard College Hellenic Society is to promote fellowship among members of the Harvard student community that are of Greek origin or interested in Greece by organizing cultural, social and educational activities. The Society will seek to welcome and help out the newly admitted students, promote fellowship within the current Hellenic community and foster a long term network of communication and support among its members and alumni.  Furthermore, the Harvard College Hellenic Society will aim to serve as a link to Hellenic history and culture for the Harvard campus and represent the Hellenic student body of Harvard in the Greek Boston community. \r\nThe society welcomes all students that have affiliation with or interest to learn about Greek culture and on- and off-campus activities.', 'harvardcollegehellenicsociety@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~hchs/index.php', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'September', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(943, 'Education Society', 'The Harvard College Education Society is meant to be a comprehensive organization for students with current or future interests in the field of education.  The organization shall serve as a forum for discussion of educational issues in any context through a combination of social and academic settings.  The organization shall support student interest in careers within the field of education and shall facilitate the exploration of such careers.  The organization shall provide a means for students to contribute to the field of education through publication.', 'educationsociety@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/educationsociety/', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates', 'October', 'Sep 24, 2012'),
(947, 'Global Energy Initiative', 'MISSION OF GEI: \r\n&bull;	Promote energy education and awareness throughout the Harvard community through an energy innovation speaker series, campus outreach, and meaningful partnerships with a diverse set of other student organizations.\r\n&bull;	Engage the Harvard community and its resources with the global energy community, particularly through sustainable energy deployment projects in the developing world.\r\n&bull;	Provide students interested in energy a forum to connect with one another.\r\n&bull;	Provide students interested in energy a unique opportunity to collectively work on energy projects that have real impact.', 'harvardgei@gmail.com', 'harvardgei.com', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'February', 'Oct 11, 2012'),
(948, 'Southeast Asian Coalition', 'The HCSAC seeks to:\r\n&bull;	Institutionalize cooperation among the Southeast Asian clubs on campus through the formation of an umbrella group;\r\n&bull;	Promote and foster stronger inter-club ties through social events;\r\n&bull;	Collectively promote discussion and educate the community about various issues facing Southeast Asia; and\r\n&bull;	Build a network in Harvard and Southeast Asia for student opportunities in internships, research, and travel, thereby creating more opportunities for Harvard College students.', 'johngobok@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/filipino/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'January', 'Oct 11, 2012'),
(950, 'Sports Marketing Club', 'The overall goal of the Harvard College Sports Marketing Club is to provide students with an outlet to explore Sports Marketing as a potential career path or interest.  \r\n\r\n	SMC aims to (1) provide informative learning about the Sports Marketing industry, (2) discuss actual case studies, and (3) involve students with Sports Marketing initiatives through the Harvard Athletic Department.\r\n\r\n	SMC hopes to bring in at least one guest speaker per semester that promotes information about Sports Marketing to the entire College.  We also hope to take field trips to Sporting Facilities.', 'sportsmarketing@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'October', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(958, 'Veterans Engagement Initiative', 'The overarching goal of HCHH will be to unite veterans, Harvard students, and community members in public service.\r\n\r\nHCHH will work to achieve this goal in four main ways: by 1) increasing student awareness of the fact that veterans are assets, not charity cases, and want to hear &ldquo;we still need you&rdquo; as well as &ldquo;thank you&rdquo; 2) facilitating student involvement in organizations that help as well as challenge and engage veterans, like The Mission Continues and The Real Warriors Campaign, in order to support veterans&rsquo; efforts to contribute to the wellbeing of our society 3) creating a more veteran-friendly environment on campus by connecting veterans with undergraduates through the common goal of service 4) hosting service projects throughout the year in Cambridge and Boston that bring together veterans and non-veterans alike.\r\n\r\nHCHH will work year-round to help veterans continue in public service after their military careers have ended, as well as to increase undergraduate appreciation for what veterans have to offer as civic assets. We hope that this organization will help lead to a fundamental shift in the way veterans are viewed both on campus and around the country and inspire undergraduates to a lifetime of public service.', 'harvardcollegehelpingheroes@gmail.com', 'hcvei.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'January', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(962, 'Community Garden', 'We are the primary maintenance and management organization of the Harvard Community Garden, located at 27 Holyoke Place. The Community Garden student group works in collaboration with various administrators across the University (Center for Health and the Global Environment, HUDS, Food Literacy PRoject) in all aspects of upkeep from planting to distribution to  planning and implementing programmatic uses of the garden as an educational and social space.', 'harvardgardeners@gmail.com', 'http://chge.med.harvard.edu/gardenblog/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'November', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(963, 'Global China Connection', 'The goal of Harvard College Global China Connection (HGCC) is the encouragement of social, cultural, business, and philanthropic exchange between China and the Harvard undergraduate community. This will be achieved through the development of working relationships with university groups in China, the creation of interactive events bringing together the greater Harvard and Boston community, and the promotion of greater collaboration  between the many Asian and leadership oriented interests on campus. HGCC aims to: (1) cultivate friendships between Harvard, China, and the international community by creating a global network of future leaders, (2) promote greater understanding of China on campus through collaborative programs with the extensive network of graduate schools, research centers, and alumni and student organizations of the Harvard community, (3) establish publications for Harvard students to create media content to be seen by GCC&rsquo;s international audience, and (4) provide access to Harvard&rsquo;s undergraduate community to advertise directly through the greater GCC network extending over 40 universities.', 'harvardgcc@gmail.com', 'www.hcs.harvard.edu/~hgcc/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'December', 'Sep 19, 2012'),
(964, 'Concert Commission', 'The mission of the Harvard College Concert Commission (HCC) is to organize and present live performances for the Harvard community. Its focus is on developing shows that foster an appreciation for modern musical and other performance styles as well as to enhance the cultural and social richness of the Harvard undergraduate experience. The HCC serves as an advocate for popular contemporary music on the Harvard campus and enables students to become involved in the music and entertainment industries.', 'harvardconcerts@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'May', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(969, 'PBHA&#39;s South Boston After School Program', 'PBHA&rsquo;s South Boston After School (SAS) is an arts-based literacy program for low-income youth who reside in South Boston. SAS utilizes an enrichment curriculum to promote the positive youth development of first and second graders who attend the James F. Condon Elementary School. SAS strives to empower youth through an academic enrichment and arts-based literacy curriculum, emphasizing academic confidence, conflict resolution, interdependence, prevention of risk-taking behaviors, and respect for diversity. Each Monday and/or Wednesday (2:00 &ndash; 5:30 PM), tutors will support one or two students with their homework and then participate in group-wide workshop activities. SAS participants and volunteers also attend events like field trips and Family Fun Nights so that students, families, and volunteers can build meaningful relationships. SAS also builds upon connections made over the summer by providing programming for the same students served by the South Boston Outreach Summer program.', 'spammal@college.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'February', 'Feb 23, 2011');
INSERT INTO `activities` (`id`, `name`, `description`, `email`, `website`, `size`, `members`, `election`, `osl_updated`) VALUES
(972, 'Biotechnology Association', 'The Harvard Undergraduate Biotechnology Association will seek to educate members about various aspects of the biotechnology and pharmaceutical industries through meetings, seminars, guest speakers, and various on- and off-campus events. Outside guest speakers and Harvard professors will headline meetings. Science news, business of science news, and economics of science news will be topics of discussion. Opportunities at Harvard, off campus, and after college will be pursued, and networking at various events encouraged.', 'biotechassoc@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'February', 'Oct 31, 2012'),
(975, 'Advertising and Marketing Club', 'The goal of the Club is to centralize interest in advertising and marketing on campus into a productive hub for students. Our goal is to create an organization that informs and trains future business leaders to tackle the ever-changing demands within this new and fast-paced field. By putting on workshops, competing at a national level, and organizing conferences, this organization will serve a growing population interested in advertising, while sparking interest to better inform the casual consumer of advertising content.', 'admarketingharvard@gmail.com', 'http://hcs.harvard.edu/adandmarketing', '76-100', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Oct 31, 2012'),
(981, 'German Club', 'German Club provides its members opportunities to enrich their understanding of German language and the cultural life of German-speaking countries. It also hosts casual social events so members can get to know each other and practice their German skills, whether by chatting over chicken wings at the Queen&#39;s Head during a weekly Stammtisch or by relaxing with an interesting German-language movie at Filmabend. Literary-minded students are encouraged to submit their short works to the Club&#39;s German-language broadsheet.  Outings to local German-language events (such as trips to the opera) are also planned.', 'gerclub@fas.harvard.edu', 'http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~gerclub/GerClub/Willkommen.html', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'May', 'Sep 21, 2012'),
(983, 'Baroque Chamber Orchestra', 'The award-winning Harvard College Baroque Chamber Orchestra is a musical ensemble that has been active in and around Harvard for nearly 20 years. It is the only orchestra on campus that is specifically focused on Baroque repertoire. Our goals are:\r\n&bull;To provide a safe, enjoyable place for musicians to develop their musical talents\r\n&bull;To teach, perform and promote the techniques and pieces of Baroque composers\r\n&bull;To educate the Harvard, greater Boston and New England communities about Baroque music and encourage listeners to support its perpetuation\r\n\r\nThe orchestra performs two major concerts a year in the Memorial Church and a handful of chamber music recitals in locations around campus. Notable guest performers include soprano Dominique LaBelle, tenor Frank Kelley and keyboardist Ton Koopman.', 'harvardbaroque@gmail.com', 'http://www.harvardbaroque.org', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(987, 'Sustained Dialogue', 'Harvard College Sustained Dialogue (HCSD) is concerned with facilitating continuous structured dialogues about- but not restricted to- identity issues among groups of undergraduates with the hope of empowering each to recognize and address social injustice such that the sum total of their raised awareness and activity will translate into a more welcoming and cohesive campus.', 'harvardsdialogue@gmail.com', '', '51-75', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(993, 'International Healthcare Initiative', 'The Harvard College International Healthcare Initiative (HCIHI) is concerned with improving the quality of healthcare in developing countries by supplying hospitals and clinics in the developing world with donated medical equipment and supplies. The equipment and supplies will be donated by local Boston hospitals which would otherwise be discarded due to surplus, changes in technology, or changing American medical regulations. Once these items are collected from the various hospitals and healthcare institutions, the members will assemble to clean and sort the supplies and prepare them for shipment to areas in the world where they are most needed. The Harvard College International Healthcare Initiative is an active group which, through its medical supply recovery program, will help its members increase their awareness of the vital role that each of them can play in making a difference around the world.', 'hcihi@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Oct 11, 2012'),
(997, 'Global Health Review', 'The Harvard College Global Health Review (HCGHR) is the first student-led publication covering global health issues to emerge at Harvard University. Founded in the Fall 2008 by a small group of students from the Harvard College Global Health and AIDS Coalition, the HCGHR aims to raise the levels of both scholarship and awareness in relation to global health. It is the hope of the HCGHR staff that the information brought forth in the review will help to inspire and educate current and future global health leaders. The HCGHR is available both in print and online.', 'hcghreview@gmail.com', 'www.hcs.harvard.edu/hghr', '51-75', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'December', 'Oct 31, 2012'),
(1002, 'Students For Education Reform', 'Students for Education Reform (SFER) provides undergrads with the opportunity to get involved in the education reform movement and work towards equal opportunity for all American children. We do this in five ways: (1) we do direct service (tutoring, helping high schoolers with the college application process, and helping out local schools in one-day service projects); (2) we engage in local education politics through advocacy work; (3) we hold events on campus to raise awareness of the achievement gap; (4) we hold a weekly discussion series to learn more about the latest education policy and research; and (5) we work to build a tight-knit community for Harvard students interested in education. For more information, please contact harvard@studentsforedreform.org or explore our website at http://sferharvard.wordpress.com/.', 'harvard@studentsforedreform.org', 'http://sferharvard.wordpress.com/', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1008, 'Gap Year Harvard College', 'The Harvard Gap Year Group is concerned with the well-being and success of Harvard students regarding taking time off from school. The group will seek to promote the option of taking time off, to provide resources and support for students considering or currently taking time off, and to provide a social community for students upon returning from time off. These services will be provided to the Harvard community by appropriate means such as web resources, publications, meetings, seminars, and peer support. Additionally, the group intends to work alongside the Office of Admissions to ensure that its services and informational materials are made known to students who may be considering a gap year before beginning their freshman year.', 'gap-year@hcs.harvard.edu', 'hcs.harvard.edu/gap-year', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1009, 'Poetry Society', 'The objective of the Harvard College Poetry Society is to provide interested Harvard students with a forum for the discussion and performance of poetry, with a particular focus on the genre&rsquo;s oral element. We intend to consider poetry of all kinds, from contemporary student-composed pieces to the great works of Chaucer and Byron. We plan to extend our performance and discussion model to poetry in foreign languages, depending on the interest of our membership. We also plan to invite guest speakers and performers to the college to meet with our organization and we would like to host a biannual open-mike night. Finally, we will serve as a launching point and support system for Harvard undergraduate poets who are interested in participation in local performance poetry and slam competitions. Our organization endeavors to connect kindred lovers of poetry with one another and to connect poetry itself to the campus at large.', 'hcps@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1010, 'Czech and Slovak Society', 'To provide opportunities for Czech and Slovak students, as well as other College students and alumni to meet, discuss and share experiences. The Harvard College Czech and Slovak Society strives to spread awareness on campus about Czech, Slovak and Czechoslovak culture, society, history, politics and current events. We also aim to raise awareness and provide support for schools and students in the Czech Republic and Slovakia about the possibilities of studying at Harvard College and in the United States.', '', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'September', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1013, 'Gay, Lesbians, Or, Whatever (GLOW)', 'GLOW is a safe and accountable space for students of color at Harvard who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, same-gender loving, transgender, queer or who are simply questioning or exploring their current identity.  GLOW recognizes that our identities as People of Color and our Queer experiences are inseparable from one another; and we seek to raise awareness of this truth on campus. GLOW primarily serves as safe-space that facilitates dialogue, builds communities, and works towards gaining visibility through traditions, active leadership, and pride. In addition GLOW also aims to honor the advances made by Queer People of Color amid various geopolitical, sociological, and institutional pressures, as well as identify what being a Queer Person of Color means and what the community represents. Most centrally, GLOW aims to empower members to embrace all components of their identity and feel comfortable expressing them on campus and beyond.', 'harvardglow@gmail.com', 'harvardglow.org', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'May', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(1024, 'Pakistan Student Association', 'Our mission is to promote interest in and awareness of Pakistani culture and current affairs within the Harvard undergraduate community. Through events that bring Pakistan to the fore and stimulate further dialogue, HCPSA aims to cater to a diverse community interested in developing an understanding of Pakistan: its culture, affairs and issues.', 'harvardpsa@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/harvardpsa', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'May', 'Nov 28, 2012'),
(1025, 'US-India Initiative', 'The goals of the Harvard College US-India Initiative (HCUII) are two-fold: to foster initial interactions and long-term cooperation between youth from the United States and India and to leverage these relationships to address some of India&rsquo;s most pressing social and economic issues.\r\n\r\nThe initiative approaches these goals through two primary methods: 1) conferences organized in major Indian cities bringing college students from the US and India together for a series of panels, speakers, and collaborative case study resolution and 2) interaction online through a closed social network which facilitates further conversations and long-term relationships.', 'fthumpasery@gmail.com', 'usindiainitiative.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1028, 'Scandinavian Society', 'The Harvard College Scandinavian Society is concerned with the political, social and cultural issues regarding Scandinavia, meaning Norway, Sweden, Denmark, Iceland, Finland, and all the territories of the aforementioned nations. The group will seek to promote greater awareness and understanding of these issues in the Harvard community by appropriate means such as publications, meetings, discussions, films, cultural activities, and other educational activities.', 'harvardscandinaviansociety@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/scandinaviansoc/', '76-100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'November', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1029, 'Science Club for Girls', 'Harvard College Science Club for Girls brings Harvard undergraduate scientists and local grade school students together in free after school activities that focus on increasing self-confidence and science literacy.  K-12th grade girls work with mentor-scientists (you!) who model and foster leadership, affirm college as an expectation, and promote careers in science and technology as goals and options.  Undergraduate students will inspire girls in grades K-12 at nearby Cambridge and Boston schools through activities, fieldtrips, speaker events, and after school programs.  Training, supplies, support, and flexible, hands-on science curriculum are provided.', 'scfg.harvard@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/scfg/', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(1033, 'Venture Partners', 'The mission of Harvard College Venture Partners (HCVP) is to provide students with the knowledge, skills and community to maximize their chances of successfully launching technology ventures.\r\n\r\nBy bringing together leadership in technology and entrepreneurship across the schools of Harvard as well as alumni, we have cultivated a network of resources, advice, and mentorship to help students at any stage of the startup process further develop their ventures. \r\n\r\nBy working closely with the Harvard Innovation Lab, Harvard Business School Startup Tribe, and organizations and startups across Boston, we are actively fostering a community of entrepreneurs interested in applying their learnings in computer science and other technical backgrounds to creating impactful companies.', 'partners@hcvp.co', 'wwww.hcvp.co', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'March', 'Dec 04, 2012'),
(1034, 'Actuarial Society', 'The Harvard College Actuarial Society HCAS is concerned with promoting careers and information in actuarial science. Harvard Actuarial Society is a pre-professional student-led organization established with the purpose of introducing students to careers in actuarial science and related fields. As well as raising awareness of the actuarial profession at Harvard College, the group strives to provide a forum for networking with professionals and Harvard alumni involved in fields related to actuarial science through events and discussion panels. The group will offer timelines, resources, and guidance for helping students pass examinations.', 'hcas@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'October', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1041, 'Harvard Undergraduates Raising Autism Awareness! (HURAA!)', 'HURAA serves two purposes: advocacy and outreach for the autistic community. HURAA aims to raise autism awareness within Harvard University through various advocacy events. HURAA also seeks to improve the lives of families living with autism in Cambridge and in the greater Boston area - providing community space and social connection.', 'autism.harvard@gmail.com', 'http://www.harvardautism.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1042, 'Social Innovation Collaborative', 'The mission of the Harvard College Social Innovation Collaborative is to bring together Harvard undergraduates, graduate students and broader community members who are passionate about social innovation and its ability to create meaningful and sustainable social change through mixed-profit models. SIC seeks to create a productive, open dialogue about social entrepreneurship, foster and incubate innovative ideas, and promote collaboration. Specifically, this collaboration will be formed through the partnership of like-minded organizations across Harvard&#39;s colleges and the greater Boston community and will consist of topical discussion forums with co-sponsors, including pre-career and student-led organizations, an open list-serve to share relevant articles, events, and internship opportunities, and the development of an Advisory Council through which graduate students and professors will serve and mentor club participants. Events will include informational and networking sessions with professionals, thematic panels, and informal meals and workshops with innovators, providing a forum for dynamic perspectives on social entrepreneurship. SIC is also committed to organizing the annual Igniting Innovation Summit on Social Entrepreneurship, which brings together leading social entrepreneurs and interested students to discuss developments in the field and foster a community of social innovators.', 'hcsic@hcs.harvard.edu', 'sicollaborative.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'November', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1043, 'Just Peace at Harvard College', 'Just Peace at Harvard College supports Israel as a democratic home for the Jewish people, the full and equal rights of Arab and other non-Jewish citizens of Israel and the right of the Palestinian people to a state of their own. Just Peace is an organization dedicated to social justice in Israel/Palestine.', '', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1047, 'Council for Cuban American National Advocacy', 'The Harvard College Council for Cuban American National Advocacy (CCANA) is committed to creating awareness of human rights violations in Cuba and providing support for activists and civil society groups on the island. CCANA is not a cultural organization but rather one rooted in protecting human rights. The organization actively encourages all students, regardless of age or ethnicity, to become members. CCANA members are not expected to be Hispanic or knowledgeable of Cuban issues but instead demonstrate passion and commitment in defending human rights.\r\nThe objective of CCANA is two-fold: awareness and support. CCANA will monitor the issue of human rights in Cuba and develop awareness of the continued violations in Cuba as well as highlight the efforts of Cuban activists. In addition, CCANA members will communicate with activists on the island and related international organizations to directly support the efforts to achieve Human Rights in Cuba.\r\nCCANA will work on a number of current projects as well as projects specifically developed by the CCANA members. The Harvard CCCANA will engage the College and Local communities in a way that is both fun and conscience of our mission. Events like the Con La Misma Moneda bake sale, which forces students to convert their money into another currency before using it, will help put Cuban issues like economic apartheid in terms that are understandable and appropriate for the college audience.\r\nCCANA will also host Salsa Dancing, art exhibitions, and movie screenings to appeal to the broader community while still accomplishing the group&rsquo;s mission. In line with reaching a broad community, CCANA seeks to work with other Human Rights student organizations to host events or participate in activities.\r\nCCANA is different than other organizations on campus, such as Cuban American Undergraduate Student Organization (CAUSA) because it has the mission of political activism and awareness. CAUSA&rsquo;s mission is to bring the Cuban-American students together in a comfortable social atmosphere in order to celebrate the Cuban culture. CCANA, however, intends to spread awareness to people of all nationalities and host events that will give support to dissidents in Cuba and aim towards a transition to democracy on the island.\r\nHarvard CCANA will be able to leverage past experiences and best practices learned to ensure successful management of the organization. Furthermore, as a CANF- recognized chapter, Harvard CCANA will benefit from a generous organization that will provide both financial and administrative support through out the life of the chapter. In order to receive assistance, the Harvard CCANA chapter will send a formal email request to the UCCANF National Director describing the desired level of support, whether for an annual budget or a specific event. This support is offered freely on behalf of CANF to the individual College organizations upon request and does not hold chapters liable for repayment. Therefore, the Harvard College Council for Cuban American National Advocacy would have no requirements or ties to the parent organization other than financial support and assistance whenever requested by the chapter itself.', 'cana@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1063, 'PBHA&#39;s Roxbury Youth Initiative Term', 'n/a', 'katejsim@gmail.com', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Jun 28, 2011'),
(1064, 'PBHA&#39;s Recent Immigrant Term-Time Enrichment (RITE)', 'n/a', 'rite@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'January', 'Jun 29, 2011'),
(1066, 'Undergraduate Alumni Connection', 'Section A. The Harvard Undergraduate Alumni Connection exists to build and strengthen connections between the Harvard undergraduate and alumni populations.  The relationship between these two groups benefits students and alumni alike, and is a critical component of the health of the University as a whole.  The Harvard Undergraduate Alumni Connection seeks to serve this purpose through a three-pronged approach of connectivity, leadership development, and outreach.  We will provide events and programming that allow students and alumni to connect to each other in-person and virtually.  We will provide opportunities for undergraduates to assume roles of class leadership after graduation, providing the structure for strong classes and community in the recent graduate years, which are critical to long-term engagement with the University.  We will serve as a conduit of communication that flows through students and alumni, providing information about opportunities to connect with each other and the University.  In our efforts, we will work in conjunction with the Harvard Alumni Association&#39;s College and Alumni Outreach Building Communities Committee.', 'huac@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'August', 'Aug 27, 2012'),
(1068, 'High Impact Philanthropy', 'Harvard High Impact Philanthropy seeks to promote a culture of giving more, and giving more effectively, to charitable causes. We believe in trying to use our money and resources to prevent human suffering, and we believe in finding the most effective ways to do so.\r\n\r\n$25 well spent can add one healthy year to a person&rsquo;s life, but only if deployed in the right ways. We believe that efficiency multiplies the effectiveness of any given effort, and that effectiveness can be studied and quantified.\r\n\r\nHHIP is interested in finding the most effective ways both do and promote this. Some of our more dedicated members and affiliates donate 10% of their income to proven effective charities, while others undertake charity research and other philanthropic ventures.\r\n\r\nWe&rsquo;re also interested in many related questions. How do we find the charities that are most effective? Is our impact greater working in high-paying jobs, and donating more money than we could otherwise? Are there more effective strategies than personally donating? We discuss these questions ourselves and bring in speakers from across the country and the world for panels and talks to reach a broader audience.\r\nDonating 10% of your income works out to $330,000 for the average college grad -- enough to save about 200 lives if given to today&rsquo;s most effective organizations. We encourage donating significant portions of one&rsquo;s income to charities, and making sure that the charities we choose have been effectively demonstrated to save lives efficiently. Some of our more dedicated members donate, or pledge to donate, more than 10% of their income (although we certainly don&rsquo;t ask for or expect any commitment)! \r\n\r\nHHIP is interested in many related issues: how do we find out which charities are the most effective? Should we choose a career that maximizes the amount of money we will be able to give? Are there more effective strategies than personally donating, like persuading others to donate or undertaking valuable charity-related research? We discuss these questions ourselves and organize talks, panels and other events to get the rest of the campus interested.', 'harvardhip@gmail.com', 'http://harvardhip.org/', '1-9', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1070, 'Happiness Project', 'The Happiness Project promotes well-being, happiness, and stress reduction among Harvard undergraduate students. We aim to educate about and reduce stress through play and self-discovery. In addition, we aim to raise awareness of the serious negative psychological effects of stress on individuals and the student body as a whole. Members staff a drop-in center &quot;The HappyNest&quot; which houses a variety of innately fun, stress-free activities, items, and resources.We also plan and host events, lectures, and programs that support a low stress, fun, and healthy lifestyle.', 'happiness@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/happiness/index.php', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'March', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1071, 'Sexual Health Education &amp; Advocacy throughout Harvard College', 'Sexual Health Education &amp; Advocacy throughout Harvard College (SHEATH) is dedicated to empowering members of the Harvard community to explore their experiences with love and sex by providing comprehensive programming addressing a wide range of issues relating to sex, relationships, dating, sexual health, and sexuality through SHEATH&#39;s conclusive event, Sex Week at Harvard. SHEATH aims to unite diverse members of Harvard&#39;s community, as well as the greater Cambridge/Boston community, by promoting open, honest, holistic, culturally competent, and inclusive sexual health education and discussion. Through the collaborative effort of Sex Week, SHEATH seeks to connect individuals and communities both within and beyond Harvard through common human experiences with love, sex, sexuality, and relationships.', 'sexweek@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://hcs.harvard.edu/sexweek', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Oct 11, 2012'),
(1074, 'Three Letter Acronym', 'Three Letter Acronym practices and performs the Harold, a specific format of long form improvisation. The Harold is most famously performed at New York&#39;s The Upright Citizens Brigade and Chicago&#39;s Improv Olympic and has shot some of your favorite SNL and Thursday Night Comedy stars to fame (Amy Poehler, Donald Glover, Bobby Moynihan, Aubrey Plaza).', 'tlaimprov@hcs.harvard.edu', 'tlaimprov.com', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1078, 'Candela Dance Troupe', 'Harvard Candela Dance Troupe is a student run dance group that performs Latin dance at a variety of Harvard events. We are a non-competitive dance group that seeks to promote Latin dance in the Harvard community and create ties between Latin American students and the greater student body through the love of dance.', 'candela@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~candela/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1080, 'Digital Art Club', 'The Harvard College Digital Art Club is concerned with bringing together people of various creative interests and backgrounds to improve upon the techniques of digital graphic design through mutual teaching and learning. The club will compliment the liberal arts education by equipping its members with tangible skills of not only recreational but also professional use. Finally, the club seeks to bridge the gap between the current professional art department at Harvard and interested students who might not be able to devote themselves professionally to arts during their college career, but still would like to advance their skills at their own pace.', 'hdac-board@lists.hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~digiart/', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 11, 2012'),
(1082, 'Jazz Bands', 'Founded in 1971, the Harvard University Jazz Bands strive to promote awareness and appreciation of jazz on campus through annual performances, hosting of guest artists, and commissioning of new works. There are two jazz bands at Harvard: the Monday Band--conducted by founder Tom Everett, the Director of Bands at Harvard--focuses on the music of Duke Ellington, Charles Mingus, and classic and contemporary big band literature, and tends to be a greater time commitment (rehearsals 2 nights a week). The Sunday Band--directed by Assistant Director of Bands Mark Olson--plays primarily the music of Count Basie and other classic swing, and only rehearses once a week. We hold auditions in the first two weeks of fall semester to determine placement into the two bands. Both bands perform in separate concerts and jointly host performances. Recent guest artists have included Benny Golson, Roy Haynes, Eddie Palmieri, Jimmy Heath, and Cecil McBee.', 'jazz-monday@lists.hcs.harvard.edu', 'www.harvardjazz.org', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1083, 'Generalist', 'The Generalist aims to foster interdisciplinary collaboration between conventionally distinct branches of knowledge, through contemporary artistic strategies.\r\n\r\nWe want to produce art for this community&mdash;for budding thinkers who are excited by their disciplines. \r\n\r\nWe believe that the only way forge the interdisciplinary connections that are part of Harvard mission is by implementing small, sustained, temporary ruptures in the methodology traditionally implemented by each discipline, as exercises. In the digital age, representations of knowledge and access to information can be material, spatial, tangible&mdash;and we should perceive our tangible world as containing an enormous amount of information.\r\n\r\nWe emphasize that exposure to and participation in art can stimulate the development of tools for creative problem solving, helping students become better scientists and humanists, better lawmakers and businesspeople, better engineers and administrators.\r\n\r\nThe Generalist will provide a venue for wit, mockery, irony, games, puzzles, and other forms of play within a contemporary arts discourse. We are a productive organization rather than a social one, in that the activity of the club is centered on producing projects for the consumption of people in the community, outside the club.', 'harvardgeneralist@gmail.com', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'November', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(1084, 'Grief Support: Actively Moving Forward', 'The purpose of Students of AMF at Harvard College is to provide peer support for college students grieving the illness or death of a loved one and empower the campus community to take action through service.', 'studentsofamf@hcs.harvard.edu', 'www.hcs.harvard.edu/studentsofamf', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Sep 11, 2012'),
(1085, 'Wine Society', 'Pliny the Elder&rsquo;s wise words &ldquo;in vino veritas&rdquo; illustrate the belief that in wine there is truth. To illuminate another interpretation of the old Latin adage, the Harvard College Wine Society was founded in 2011 with the philosophy of re-establishing the European tradition of respecting and revering wine.\r\n\r\nConcerned with the culture of binge drinking on college campuses, we aim to promote social drinking in a responsible environment by cultivating an appreciation and understanding of wine. We provide a common space for undergraduate students, graduate students, and faculty members to meet and interact through the enjoyment of wine.\r\n\r\nWe arrange a number of tastings throughout the semester. The majority of tastings are organized by grape variety and showcase wines from all around the world. Tastings are hosted by connoisseurs and more experienced members of the Society. We also invite guest speakers such as winemakers and wine educators to give lectures on various topics in oenology, including viniculture and vinification. Lastly, we hold wine and cheese pairing events where students have the chance to mix and mingle with faculty members and graduate students.', 'wine@hcs.harvard.edu', 'www.hcs.harvard.edu/wine/', '76-100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1086, 'Dominican Students Association', 'The Harvard Dominican Students Association aims to sponsor educational, social, and service events in order to address issues concerning the Dominican community within and outside of Harvard College. We seek to create an inclusive space that promotes dialogue and spreads awareness of Dominican history, culture, and politics.', 'harvarddsa@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1087, 'Alzheimer&#39;s Buddies', 'Alzheimer&rsquo;s Buddies is a response to the profound isolation and social disengagement experienced by people in the intermediate-to-late-stages of Alzheimer&#39;s disease (AD). It pairs local students with Alzheimer&#39;s buddies so that they might form meaningful relationships over the course of a semester or longer.  Our initiative encourages students to take the mindset of a friend rather than of a care provider, to learn about their patients&#39; past and passions, to establish real friendships.  This interaction not only provides patients with a unique outlet, but also provides students with a formative experience and formal training on this devastating disease.', 'hcalzbuddies@hcs.harvard.edu', 'hcs.harvard.edu/hcalzbuddies', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(1094, 'Lebanese Club', 'The Lebanese Club is an apolitical, nonprofit, nonpartisan organization that shall remain free in its programming and official rhetoric from any affiliation with or bias towards inter-Lebanese political, religious, or sectarian entities and ideologies. The Lebanese Club is concerned with spreading the Lebanese culture on campus and fostering a spirit of cultural exchange. The Lebanese Club aims to facilitate the ties between Lebanese students and the rest of the Harvard student body.', 'hclc@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'December', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(1098, 'Voice Actors&#39; Guild', 'The HCVAG is concerned with promoting the use of voice as an art medium, including but not limited to accents, character voices, and voice production for stage, film, and radio.  The group will be available to other organizations on campus as well as academic departments who wish to employ the skills of voice actors.', 'guild-list@lists.hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1099, 'Speak Out Loud', 'Speak Out Loud (SOL) is an inclusive community of artists dedicated to creating and promoting original spoken word poetry at Harvard. While our focus is spoken word, we also embrace and encourage collaboration with other student groups to foster new conversations. We maintain that poetry thrives on emotion as well as analysis, and we emphasize both the personal journey of writing and the public one of performance. Most fundamentally, we believe that by telling our own stories without self-censorship or perfectionism, we can build an accepting community where we challenge ourselves to approach issues of identity honestly and creatively. SOL welcomes all who wish to write or listen, regardless of experience or affiliation.', 'Speak-out-loud@hcs.harvard.edu', 'www.harvardsol.com', '76-100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'September', 'Sep 24, 2012'),
(1100, 'Mathematica Club', 'The Harvard College Mathematica Club&#39;s goal is to help individuals in the Harvard Undergraduate and Graduate community to use Wolfram Mathematica (a computer programming language) and implement in the work that they do (i.e. problem sets, thesis work, homework, papers, etc,.) Mathematica Club is committed to helping individuals with all levels of Mathematica experience.', '', 'http://iacs.seas.harvard.edu/student-activities/harvard-mathematica-club', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'January', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1105, 'Southern Student Association', 'The mission of the Southern Student Association is to celebrate Southern American heritage, provide a support network for Harvard&#39;s southern community, and encourage campus dialogue concerning Southern American culture through various panels and social events.', 'ssa@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates', 'October', 'Sep 26, 2012'),
(1114, 'Deepam', 'Deepam exists to unite people who share a passion for Indian classical dance on campus. In addition, this group seeks to inspire enthusiasm in the larger community for this vibrant, energetic and graceful tradition. By performing in cultural shows and intercollegiate competitions throughout the year, Deepam maintains its presence on campus and in the Boston area.', '', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'May', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1115, 'International Women&#39;s Rights Collective', 'The Harvard College International Women&rsquo;s Rights Collective (IWRC) is a student organization that seeks to promote sustained dialogue and activism among undergraduates regarding international women&rsquo;s issues.  Our hope is to establish greater commitment to gender equality across borders in the framework of universal human rights. We aspire to de-stigmatize contentious elements of gender and cultural relativism through productive, interactive, and respectful debates and events.\r\n\r\nValue Statement\r\nAs a Harvard student organization, we recognize our inherent contextualization within Western gender ideology. But the problems we hope to address in the world are contextualized as well. In order to understand the sources of gender conflict and explore sustainable solutions, we reject the notion of culture as a static, unchanging entity. Instead, we hope to work creatively within cultural frameworks to reduce human suffering on the basis of gender.', 'hciwrc@gmail.com', 'http://www.facebook.com/hciwrc', '76-100', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Dec 04, 2012'),
(1122, 'Holocaust and Genocide Awareness Council', 'Harvard holds a strong commitment to protecting the civil liberties of those blessed with the gift of life, whether they live in the US or abroad. Martin Luther King Jr, the great civil activist, once proclaimed, &ldquo;an injustice anywhere, is a threat to justice everywhere!&rdquo; Dr. King&rsquo;s wise words resonate within this organization&rsquo;s mind because this organization aims to raise awareness and battle one of the world&rsquo;s greatest injustices: genocide. \r\n\r\nWe aim to remember past genocides like the Holocaust and battle against the genocides inflicting our globe. This organization is a multi-faith and multi-ethnic club that will bring together Africans, Yugoslavians, Armenians, Jews, Christians, Muslims, etc and use the combination to combat genocide. As such, the purpose of the Harvard College Holocaust and Genocide Awareness Council is to raise awareness about the Holocaust and genocides world-wide and raise funds to help battle genocide through awareness and donating money to the victims of genocide. Those who fail to understand the past are doomed to repeat it. It is our vision to break the cycle and see genocide ended.', '', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Sep 21, 2012'),
(1124, 'Society of Latino Engineers and Scientists', 'The Harvard College Society of Latino Engineers and Scientists aims to recruit, retain and graduate more minority students in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics in order to increase the diversity in such fields at the College and at large. Our organization will work to advance student achievement through a combination of academic support, educational enrichment opportunities, and most important through community building at the College. This organization benefits not only minority students, but other undergraduates as well. A more diverse student body in the sciences and engineering will enrich the educational experience of every student. Diversity helps us learn to communicate with people from different beliefs, experiences, and perspectives. The ever-changing demographics of the nation require that undergraduates develop the skills necessary to work with people of different backgrounds.', 'hsles@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'February', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1129, 'Munch', 'Harvard College Munch is a group for student interested in kink and alternative sexualities to meet, and organize relevant events&mdash;speakers, discussions, and screenings. It exists to promote a positive and accurate understanding of alternative sexualities and kink on campus, as well as to create a space where college-age adults may reach out to their peers and feel accepted in their own sexuality.\r\n\r\nHarvard College Munch therefore meets an otherwise unaddressed need on campus. Though existing campus groups range from representing women and men, queer sexualities and orientations, all the way to groups dedicated to abstinence, no other group exists as a forum for students interested in alternative sexualities to explore their identities and develop a community with their peers.', 'harvardmunchman@gmail.com', 'http://www.hcs.harvard.edu/~munch/ (not yet active)', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'February', 'Nov 30, 2012'),
(1130, 'Nostalgics', 'The Nostalgics are concerned with the celebration and dissemination of soul and Motown music across Harvard campus, and throughout the greater Boston area.  We hope to inculcate in our listeners and musicians an appreciation for the power of this music and the strong, positive emotional bond it can form.  Through our concerts on Harvard Campus, we hope to boost morale and encourage people to revisit a music that has been important to all of us.  For the members of our group, we hope to provide a fulfilling, music-loving community, and to give our musicians the experience of playing in a semi-professional band.', 'thenostalgics@gmail.com', 'www.wearethenostalgics.com', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'March', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1132, 'Scholars at Risk', 'Harvard College Students for Scholars at Risk engages Harvard students in direct dialogue with scholars who have faced various forms of persecution for scholarship under oppressive regimes for their work and/or their various axes of identity. We provide the rare opportunity for students to form relationships with at-risk scholars that are under a protection at Harvard. Our activities \r\neducate and inspire both discourse and action surrounding both the work of the scholars and situations of persecution. Our student group provides opportunities for students to interact meaningfully with topics of human rights, literature and freedom of expression.\r\n\r\nWe provide opportunities for students to actively engage with the subjects of human rights and freedom of expression through personal scholarly and artistic endeavors. Regular student group activities involve bloging, speaker events and teas, frequent contact with at-Risk scholars, and writing Master Classes and teach-ins for leter writing. Our largest yearly collaborative endeavor is the creation of &ldquo;The Living Magazine&rdquo;, which is a dual project that produces a meaningful live event and a lasting publication.', 'hcssar@gmail.com', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates, Graduates, Community Members', 'March', 'Oct 11, 2012'),
(1134, 'CrimsonEMS', 'CrimsonEMS facilitates the opportunity for a student-run EMS as part of Harvard&#39;s extracurricular offerings. Its purpose is twofold: CrimsonEMS facilitates 1) a heavily subsidized Emergency Medical Technician-Basic (EMT-B) training course to take place at Harvard University concurrently with classes, and 2) opportunities to work aboard an ambulance run by MIT-EMS in addition to other on campus Quick Response Service (QRS) opportunities. Eventually, CrimsonEMS hopes to operate its own ambulance, which will serve the Harvard Community. We believe that the capacity to serve our community, our school, and ourselves as EMTs is tantamount to a healthy, rich, and medically aware College Community.', 'crimsonems@hcs.harvard.edu', 'crimsonems.net', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 19, 2012'),
(1137, 'Mathematics Association', 'To advance undergraduate knowledge and appreciation of mathematics, encourage social interaction among math students, and advise students interested in studying mathematics. HUMA strives to create and maintain a strong and lively community for all students interested in the mathematical sciences.', 'math@hcs.harvard.edu', 'http://hcs.harvard.edu/~math', '&gt; 100', 'Undergraduates', 'April', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1138, 'Reason and Religion', 'Harvard College Reason and Religion exists to promote sustained, thoughtful reasoning about the questions that religions, and in particular Christianity, bring to the public square and to our personal lives. Our group will promote study groups and reasoned dialogue about questions like &lsquo;Is there a God?, &lsquo;What is the meaning of life?,&rsquo; &lsquo;Why is there evil?&rsquo; and other such questions.\r\n\r\nWe especially want to provide a safe and welcoming space for Christian students who are looking for opportunities to study topics such as church history, a theology of work and vocation, and a theological integration between the teachings of the Bible and their own academic areas of study. For\r\nall students, we want to create a safe and welcoming space to rationally consider evidences for the truth of Christianity, as well as graciously and openly consider intellectual challenges to Christianity. As students indicate interest, we would create forums for considering the rational plausibility of other worldviews as well.\r\n\r\nRooted in the Christian tradition, we are inspired by Jesus&rsquo; command to &ldquo;love the Lord your God&hellip;with all of your minds.&rdquo; Rooted at Harvard, we are inspired by the motto of &ldquo;Veritas&rdquo; or truth. We believe Harvard College will be strengthened by the presence of a group which brings an academic, intellectually robust, and studied approach to the big questions of life. Our group exists to host study groups, lectures, conversations, and other events and gatherings to foster critical thinking at the intersection of reason and religion.', 'hcrr@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'April', 'Dec 04, 2012'),
(1149, 'TAMID', 'The TAMID Israel Investment Group is a student organization that connects business-minded Harvard students to the Israeli economy. TAMID&rsquo;s goal is to develop the next generation of business leaders, and connect its members with philanthropists, CEOs, and investors in Israel through educational programming, hands-on investing and consulting experience, and meaningful professional opportunities.', 'TAMID@hcs.harvard.edu', '', '26-50', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1151, 'Team HYPE', 'The purpose of Team HYPE shall be to enhance the Harvard College social scene by fostering fun and inclusive environments at undergraduate events. Additional purposes of the organization shall be to provide event and publicity-consulting services to other student organizations, as well as provide spirit and enthusiasm at a range of events, including concerts and athletic events. Our mission, through these initiatives, is to foster spirit among members of the student body and make the Harvard campus a more inclusive and enjoyable place.', 'teamhype@hcs.harvard.edu', 'hcs.harvard.edu/teamhype', '10-25', 'Undergraduates', 'December', 'Sep 28, 2012'),
(1152, 'Association of Trading', 'The purpose of this organization is to:\r\n1)	Provide an opportunity to learn the basics of financial market analysis, company specific analysis, and options and securities trading through formal presentations, speaker series, trading competitions, and round table discussions.  \r\n2)	Introduce members to trading strategies and how they apply to both stocks and options.\r\n3)	Provide members with the opportunity to practice these techniques using virtual trading simulators that remove financial barriers to trading exposure.\r\n4)	Focus on individual development as a trader and help members create strategies that are appropriate for their risk and resource profiles.\r\n5)	Allow members to contribute articles to an annual publication as well as a website that the club publishes.\r\n6)	Create a network among students interested in trading financial instruments that will stimulate critical thinking, learning, and ultimately, a better understanding of investing and trading.  \r\n7)	Introduce members to the GMAT, the standardized test required for admission to business school.', 'Hcat-exec@list.hcs.harvard.edu', '', '10-25', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'December', 'Oct 11, 2012'),
(1153, 'Private Equity Group', 'The Harvard College Private Equity Group&rsquo;s mission is to educate and train interested Harvard College students for a career in private equity. Through a combination of lectures, case studies, readings, hands-on models, and speakers, we aim to provide a complete picture of the industry for students. Our underlying goal is to create a forum where members can network with industry professionals and gain firsthand exposure to a profession with historically high barriers to entry.', '', '', '1-9', 'Undergraduates, Graduates', 'December', 'Oct 03, 2012');
